Lox 18-Apr-19 02:05 AM
@SchizoidPirate There are issues that trans women and men face that are analogous to those women suffer, namely those related to the socially constructed aspect of being a woman or a man. (edited)
Beyond that, the alt-right is just as eager to undermine trans women and men as Trans Exclusionary Radical Feminists are, so it'd be really easy for the far-right to steal radfem talking points and use them against the left. That'd be particularly bad because those talking points come from theories that are, to a certain degree, espoused by the left itself. This means that it'd require a level of leftist social theory comprehension that very few leftists have, making it extremely difficult for the typical militant from our side to argue against those ideas before they get too popular.
The alt-right stealing concepts from the left already happens without us facilitating it, so imagine when TERFs make it that easy by making anti-transgender arguments.
We're making it even easier.
Lox 18-Apr-19 02:22 AM
Furthermore, no woman is less of a woman if someone who was assigned male at birth based on the way society views their biological traits (e.g. having a penis, etc) identifies as a female. Quite the contrary, it makes being a woman not something we were born with based on exterior traits and therefore forced to enact that gender, but rather something that goes beyond anything the exterior world can interact with. This perspective not only doesn't harm cis women, but it takes the concept of gender away from the deterministic, de-personalyzing function-based definitions that have always favored a class-based society. Think about it: If you're defined by what you can give to a physically dominant group of individuals (i.e. cis men), you're fitting right into the exploitative logic of capitalism and its preceding historical forms.
If being a man is defined by being capable of physically dominating the opposite gender and having a much less involved role in the generation of life (i.e. not getting pregnant), then we're assigning to men the inherent role of a capitalistic ruling class.
Lox 18-Apr-19 02:33 AM
If being a man or a woman is trapped within biological boundaries, then the collectivization of those issues is trapped inside each person's literal body. Philosophically, any experience that is entirely restricted to any person's bodily functions and impossible to communicate to those who aren't literally inside our flesh is fundamentally doomed to complete subjectivity. If that perspective WERE true, even when a woman speaks of her experiences to another woman, the best that woman can understand is what her own flesh has felt, no matter how biologically similar the other woman is. I call this position biological inherentism, marked by the idea that only your very own eyes, ears and skin can know how you feel, which is inextricably anti-collectivistic, therefore anti-ideological and impossible to advocate for.
tl;dr TERF advocacy traps human experience within the flesh and kills any chance of fighting for it in the outside world. (edited)
Lox 18-Apr-19 02:42 AM
And in case you're wondering, I'm not trans.

Lox 28-Apr-19 07:35 PM
So, as to how to use the anti-fascist dog whistle: You build a phrase where you seem to innocently mention pressing either Ctrl Alt Del or Alt F4. Example: (In the comment section of a white supremacist dog whistle video) '' I couldn't understand what he said at (insert time in the video where someone makes a dog whistle), but luckily I could enable subtitles by pressing Alt F4''
Or '' Press Alt + Del to see this meme at 4k resolution, it looks awesome!''
The advantage of doing that is we can gaslight the nazis by pretending that we were unironically, literally just talking about shortcut keys for certain computer commands
That way they eventually become unable to engage in a debate about our callout, while we denounce them to each other.
(And for other closet commies out there)
This is our way of calling them racists, have them understand it and make them unable to confront us about it.
That alienates them and makes them defenseless against our criticism, if we use it wisely
